  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated emergency life-saving interventions to drought emergency in Southern Angola</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The main aim of this UNICEF project is to reach the most drought-affected populations through providing access to water, improved sanitation screening for malnutrition, and treatment of children with severe acute malnutrition, and maternal and infant and young child nutrition (MIYCN) counseling. UNICEF, with its implementing partners, will  screen and treat 33,384 under five children for acute malnutrition, provide refresher training for  40 health and nutrition staff on the integrated management of acute malnutrition, provide 5,942 pregnant and lactating women receiving maternal, infant, and young child nutrition (MIYCN) with counseling and reach  180,000 persons with equitable access to, and use safe water, and learn good hygiene practices. In total, 219,516 persons will be targeted, including 69092 women and 46,697 girls. UNICEF also expects 4,152 people with disabilities to be among those targeted</narrative>
  </description>
